# Day 9 - Ports and Services

**Date:** January 8,2026.

---

## What is a port

A port is a numbered doorway on a machine. When a service wants to
receive connections it picks a port number and listens on it.

Think of it like this — the IP address gets you to the building,
the port gets you to the right room.

Ports go from 0 to 65535. The well-known ones (0-1023) are
standardised. Above that its more flexible.

---

## What is a service

A service is a program running on a machine that listens on a specific
port and does something useful (or dangerous, depending on which
side youre on).

Some ports i need to know by memory:

| Port | Protocol | What its used for |
|------|----------|-------------------|
| 22   | SSH      | Remote login, encrypted |
| 80   | HTTP     | Websites, unencrypted |
| 443  | HTTPS    | Websites, encrypted |
| 21   | FTP      | File transfers |
| 3306 | MySQL    | Database |
| 445  | SMB      | Windows file sharing |

---

## Why ports matter in pentesting

More open ports = larger attack surface. Every open port is a service.
Every service is potential entry point.

A closed port means theres nothing listening there — nothing to attack.
An open port means something is running and accepting connections.
That something might be misconfigured, outdated, or just plain vulnerable.

This is exactly why nmap exists. The first thing you do on any target
is find out what ports are open and what services are sitting behind them.

---

## The danger of outdated services

If a service is running an old version it might have known CVEs.
An unpatched SSH daemon or an old Apache version can be the difference
between a secure server and a compromised one.

When nmap returns version info (-sV flag) im not just collecting data —
im looking for anything old enough to have public exploits.

